  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-bobw\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Bottom bracket</span></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">Raceface Cinch BB92 Bottom Bracket</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">38</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\">New</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">OBS</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-bobw\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Pedals</span></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">Crankbrothers Eggbeater 1</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">NA</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\">From old build</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">NA</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-bobw\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Wheelset</span></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">Unbranded Assymetric Rims 33 mm, Pillar 1420 Spokes, DR six-bolt hubs</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">542</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\">New</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">AliExpress</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-bobw\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Tires</span></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">Continental Cross King, Bernstein Limited 29 x 2.20&#8243;</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">90</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\">New</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">OBS</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-bobw\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\">Miscellaneous</span></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">Titanium Bolts, Clarks SL Shift Cables, Elite Vico Carbon Cage</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">NA</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\">NA</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-8d8j\">NA</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\"></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-amwm\">Total price:</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-amwm\">2,860.5</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\"></td>\n    <td class=\"tg-baqh\"></td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n\n\n\n<p>Which brings us to the following question: why would you build a bike this way? If you want to ride a unique bike and not bump into a couple of similar models out on the bike park but also don&#8217;t want to spend a princely sum for the high-end models, then having a bit of patience and resourcefulness is the way to go.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>To critique, the brake hoses and cables could have been tidier and the frame finish gloss instead of matte so it&#8217;s easier to manage the scratches. And I need to get a matte finish seatpost. I will also lookout for the durability of the carbon rims.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"756\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-1340x756.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-505853\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-1340x756.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-650x367.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-190x107.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-1080x610.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142-16x9.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5142.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>So far I&#8217;ve found the bike to be nimble and quick to react â€“ probably thanks to the 69.5Âº head angle and shorter 425 mm chainstays â€“ and stable on the downhills whether on dirt or on the road. In the past I&#8217;ve always put 2.0 or 2.1&#8243; tires on my MTBs but this time, with a slightly larger diameter, plus the solid fork, this build is more capable on the new bike park trails. I assume a very experienced rider would have loads of fun on this!</p>\n\n\n\n<p>With the very low weight it obviously climbs just like a road bike, so the small little hills around old villages are no problem, neither are long climbs up to the Big Buddha.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Gallery</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-3 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"756\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/IMG_5023-134